		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32730043">They truly are. They are more than just a necessity, thay should be integral part, a cornerstone of powers (not just magic) in a setting. When there are no apparent limits we get something like Sword Art Oline or Mahouka, where blatant self-insertous Marty Stu characters ruin every bit of empathy and suspension of disbelief.<br />
One of the best examples of a 'limitations and powers' system is Pat Rothfuss' book 'The Name Of The Wind'. Not only it presents a massive ammount of a magic powers, it also explains them, categorises them and draws their non-passable limits, be it a runic magic of blacksmiths, immitation and correspodence based voodoo like sympathy or any other.<br />
But it is a shame, that not many fantasy works trouble themselves with an explanations. Even in a classic works like LotR there are no apparent limits, no bordrers, no way to tell what the limit of an any given character is. Alas.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://mal.oko.im/GooFraN" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://mal.oko.im/export/GooFraN?type=1&amp;bar1=00eecc05&amp;bar2=00dd2200&amp;line1=aaffdd00&amp;line2=aaff0000&amp;back=ffffffff&amp;font1=20220700&amp;font2=90220700&amp;title=00220700&amp;hue=45" /></a><!--center--></div></div></td>
