		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32731209">What a character can't do is often more interesting than what they can do. Limitations and weaknesses are what drive struggle, vulnerability, conflict, tension, and all those other wonderful elements we love to see present in a story.<br />
<br />
As GooFraN noted, I think that this is why most of us would agree that Sword Art Online is bad storytelling.  There are many things wrong with SAO, but chief among them is Kirito's character.  The fact that Kirito's power level is so off-the-charts insane actually makes the fights boring and undermines the conflict of the story.  When Kirito unleashes massively-powerful techniques to quickly end some fights and then doesn't use them in future fights, it leads to obvious questions about why he doesn't just immediately use his most powerful attacks to quickly end every fight, and most of the tension in later fights seems fake as a result.<br />
<br />
<br />
Without limitations in magic, many stories based around magical power cease to exist, and some very interesting stories can be born out of limitations.<br />
<br />
As an example, Death Note's first half (Light vs L) is fundamentally a conflict based on the Death Note's limitations.  The Death Note has the ability to kill people, and Light also has the ability to specify cause and time of death.  Those are interesting story hooks, but they aren't what drives the action in the series.<br />
<br />
What are the limitations of the Death Note?  For one thing, Light needs to physically write the name in the book in order to cause death.  He can't just will people to die, or cause people to die by snapping his fingers, or some other trivial action.  The Death Note, by its nature, leaves behind a paper trail, and thus represents a liability for anyone under scrutiny of investigation.  Thus, when his home comes under surveillance, Light is forced to come up with creative ways to continue to write names in the Death Note.  In a sense, Light's continued use of the Death Note is requisite, in the sense that if people stop dying when he is under scrutiny, then it becomes apparent to the investigation team that Light is somehow linked to the murders.  So this limitation of the Death Note represents a manner in which Light may be caught.  It's a source of tension.<br />
<br />
The other major limitation of the Death Note is that Light needs a name and face in order to kill.  This is ultimately what drives the conflict between Light and L, as Light cannot use the Death Note to eliminate L.  It also forces Light to creatively to circumvent this limitation, as becomes the case with the Raye Penber arc.<br />
<br />
Death Note also provides a good example of a magic that is tied to a powerful cost.  Light has access to another magic power apart from the Death Note itself: the ability to see someone's name by looking at them.  However, it comes at the cost of half of his own remaining lifespan.  Light considers this unacceptable for use by himself, which reinforces the notion that Light's goal is not ultimately to create a world that is &quot;better&quot; in any altruistic sense (he could easily achieve that in half his remaining lifespan if he traded for the eyes), but rather he is selfishly working to create a world that he can preside over as lord and emperor.  However, others (such as Misa) <em>are</em> willing to trade half their remaining lifespan for the ability to see others' names.<br />
<br />
If Light had the ability to see others' names, the conflict between him and L would end pretty swiftly.  However, because this power is tied to a powerful cost, it can be included as part of the story without undermining the central conflict.  It also tells us something about Light (and Misa), namely that Misa (and Light) value Misa's life much less than Light values his own, and that Light is confident in his ability to best L without this power.<br />
<br />
Limitations are what drive the conflict of Death Note's first season: Light must continue to write names in the Death Note without alerting the police who are watching him, and Light must also ascertain L's true name.  Without these two limitations in Light's magic power, we don't have much of a story.<br />
<br />
<br />
However, I do think it's important to note that Sanderson's second law does not assert that limitations must exist for ALL magics.  The rule, as stated, is that limitations are more important than powers, and if you want to have a story about magical powers (like a notebook that can kill people), then limitations must exist.  But there are plenty of stories with fantasy elements that aren't actually about powers.<br />
<br />
For example, Kyousougiga is a story that takes place in a magical world, and all of the main characters have magical powers to some degree.  Most of their magical powers are left unknown, and because we don't know the full extent of their magical powers, their limitations are unclear as well.  In fact, most of the main characters are &quot;overpowered&quot; to a similar extent as a lot of the characters that we like to criticize for being &quot;Mary Sue&quot; types.<br />
<br />
However, I don't see this as a problem.  The difference between Kyousougiga and something like SAO is that they present different types of plots.  SAO is a story about a boy using his magical powers to triumph over adversity, and as a result, a lack of limitations on those magical powers serve to trivialize any adversity he faces.  However, Kyousougiga is not fundamentally a story about magical powers; rather, it's a story about family that exists in a colorful world, of which magic is a part.  At its core, Kyousougiga is a story about a group of siblings, and their relationship with each other, and their relationship with their parents and their own inner conflicts and turmoil.  The conflicts are personal in nature, and as a result, it doesn't matter if the magic does not have clear limitations.  The siblings all have access to powerful magic, but their powerful magic isn't matched to the kind of abstract problems that they face.  Thus, the conflict, tension, and struggles presented in the story are preserved, even in the presence of &quot;overpowered&quot; characters.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by Kuiper, 07-19-14, 2:34 PM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
