		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32761303">I wish the writer of Mahouka Koukou no Rettousei read this essay before writing his story. Tatsuya from that show is absolutely flawless. The show keeps bringing up his apparent slowness of casting his magic, but he's got a method to go around even that, so it's not even a weakness. Therein lies one of dozens of issues I have with the show. When you have a character that has no faults, what kind of story can you tell? What makes a story interesting are the limitations of the characters; the struggles they have to go through with those limitations and usually the way they resolve things having bested their own limitations. Mahouka will have none of that.<br />
<br />
One of the many arguments I use to try and convince people that Mahouka is a terrible show is pretty simply summed up in one line in the essay:<br />
<br />
&quot;Why is he strong? Comic book aficionados might go into him drawing power from the sun, but in the end, we don&rsquo;t really care why he&rsquo;s strong. He just is.&quot;<br />
<br />
Mahouka consistently explains exactly how their magic works. I've just invented flying magic! How does it work? Well, I manipulate the gravity around myself using psion waves which causes disturbance in the air arou- oh wait, I don't actually care, nor do I remember the real explanation the show gave. It's probably less interesting than what I just came up with. But that's beside the point. I believe that any story that has &quot;magic&quot; never needs to explain how it works. We're in a world where magic exists. We're already suspending our disbelief for that already so there's no need to try convince us through exposition that the magic has a set logic behind it; we're going to assume it does.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I don't have much more to say about it. Sorry for a bit of ranting about Mahouka, but that show fits this problem perfectly.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
