		<tr>
		  <td width="135" class="forum_boardrow2" style="border-width: 0px 0px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="messageuser32761839" style="padding-bottom: 2px;"><a href="/profile/Kuiper"><strong>Kuiper</strong></a></div>
		  
		  <a href="/profile/Kuiper"><img src="http://cdn.myanimelist.net/images/useravatars/331692.png" vspace="2" border="0"></a>
		  <br>
		  Offline<br>
		  Joined: May 2010<br>
		  Posts: 74
		  </td>
		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32761839"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>Miraclezify said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>I believe that any story that has &quot;magic&quot; never needs to explain how it works. We're in a world where magic exists. We're already suspending our disbelief for that already so there's no need to try convince us through exposition that the magic has a set logic behind it; we're going to assume it does.<!--quote--></div><br />
I believe this sentiment is often articulated as &quot;audiences will accept the impossible (but not the implausible).&quot;<br />
<br />
For an example, I'll turn to the Star Trek 2009 movie reboot.  As a science fiction story, Star Trek has lots of things which are impossible: faster-than-light travel.  A &quot;red matter&quot; which can be used to create black holes.  <em>Time travel</em>.  But I never have any problems with any of these things, because they're part of the rules of the Star Trek universe.  Fundamentally, I don't care why they exist; I'm watching Star Trek specifically because I want to see a story set in a universe where we can have things like faster-than-light travel and other things that are impossible in our own world.  That's kind of the entire point of speculative fiction.<br />
<br />
So turning specifically to Star Trek (2009), I don't have a problem with the fact that &quot;red matter&quot; (a substance which can create black holes) exists.  What I <em>do</em> have a problem with is the fact that the Federation sent Spock alone, transporting a large quantity of this red matter in a small ship with minimal protection and no weapons.  In the hands of terrorists, this substance could be highly destructive.  (In fact, that's basically the premise of the entire movie: the red matter falls into the wrong hands, and the villain begins using it to destroy planets.)  Clearly, transporting a large quantity of a substance that can <em>destroy planets</em> of it would require an armed convoy of combat-ready ships ready to intercept any would-be space terrorists.  At the very least, have it carried by a star ship, heck, even a cargo ship with light armaments, or really anything more formidable than a tiny fragile one-man spacecraft.<br />
<br />
If the plot requires that the red matter be carried on an tiny unarmed ship with a one-man crew, build some limitation into the magic which requires it.  Like &quot;the red matter is unstable and reacts violently to large power sources, so it can't be transported on a large vessel like a starship.&quot;  Really, you can tell me anything and I'll probably go along with it; you're the one who gets to decide the rules.  I have no problem with the <em>impossibility</em> of the red matter and the physical rules that govern it.  What breaks my suspension of disbelief is the <em>implausibility</em> of the way that the Federation wantonly handles it; we're talking about a Federation where starships armed to the teeth with photo torpedos and phasers are routinely sent out on peaceful diplomatic missions, yet not a single one of these ships could be spared to protect the precious and potentially destructive cargo that is the red matter.<br />
<br />
You are allowed to make up rules, like &quot;this magical red matter creates black holes that destroy planets.&quot;  But you then must follow those rules and and respect the implications of the magic you've created.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by Kuiper, 07-19-14, 11:28 PM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
