		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32822307">In real life, the more OP a magic system is, the better. Though of course, having no weaknesses is still impossible, since it's never possible to achieve perfection. So this rule definitely doesn't apply to effective magic systems. <br />
<br />
However, in stories, when having no weaknesses is, in fact, possible, we want the characters to be challenged, so weaknesses are what make the magical character interesting_ we want the characters to overcome those weaknesses and grow. So the rule <em>only</em> really applies to effective stories. We want to be able to connect to the character's soft points, because we humans all have flaws and weaknesses. Stories are good because we can relate them to our lives. The reason why people wouldn't ever care about a story about a perfect person is that no one is perfect, so no one can connect to it, at all. <br />
<br />
Yes, we are interested in Superman because of the kryptonite. It shows that he has family, and a home that he had to leave. And believe it or not, everyone has a family (or at least parents), and most people have had to leave home. <br />
<br />
But if there were ever to be a superhero in real life_ please please <em>please</em> be as perfect as possible. I do not want to connect to you at all_ after all, now you're real. If someone's out there, who is magical, who is saving the world, I hope that person does not ever encounter any challenges.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/animelist/einonymous&amp;sclick=1"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://myanimelist.net/signature/einonymous.png" /></a> </div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
