		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32919271">There's a lot of unnecessary hate here going around for power fantasies.  Not every story has to rest on believable and genuinely tense conflict, sometimes they can be simple, escapist adventures.  I enjoyed the hell out of Sword Art Online's light novels and Kaze no Stigma and No Game No Life and One Punch Man, and none of the main characters of those stories have meaningful limitations.  Sure, the real tension and unpredictable plotline isn't the source of my enjoyment, but that's just as true of Cromartie High School or Mushishi and it's not really accused of being a flaw there.<br />
<br />
That's really kind of off-topic, though, because the lack of limitations in SAO <em>does</em> prevent it from having &quot;meaningful tension&quot; (though it can still have tension) and certainly from having action scenes with interesting and unpredictable resolutions.  Even if we assume action scenes with interesting and unpredictable resolutions are the goal, saying that limitations are the only way to cause those is faulty as it's pretty obvious that a character with no capabilities whatsoever is equally incapable of causing unpredictable outcomes.  The truth is just that people forget to put limitations on their magic systems much more often.  No one would care that Superman was vulnerable to green rocks if he didn't have any superpowers.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=2913"> <img src="http://i.imgur.com/Cci6bQq.png" /> </a><!--center--></div></div></td>
