		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32943871">@Laudandus: I find it interesting that you mention No Game No Life in a thread specifically discussing Sanderson's Second Law, because for all of the absurdity of protags' abstract &quot;power level,&quot; the magic in NGNL is remarkably restrained.<br />
<br />
I will concede that NGNL treats its powers with greater gravitas than its limits, but at its basic premise, NGNL looks like an underdog story.  Our protagonists represent humanity, a race with <em>zero</em> magical aptitude, and they compete against elves, beastmen, and angels who all wield powerful magics.  Sora is cunning to an almost absurd degree, but nearly every story arc revolves around examining the magic his opponent is wielding, looking for cracks and weaknesses in the magic, and exploiting them.  NGNL is very much a story that exhibits the value of limits when it comes to constructing magic systems.<br />
<br />
Apart from magic (and humans' inability to use it), NGNL does give Sora and Shiro weaknesses that are rather meaningless for most intents and purposes (most of the stuff that goes along with being a hikikomori, such as social anxiety, is mostly played for laughs).  However, I was delighted when one of the arcs focused on one of their weaknesses, leveraging it as a source of tension: the fact that Sora and Shiro operate as a &quot;single unit&quot; and have trouble operating independently becomes a big deal when Sora disappears and Shiro has to figure out the path forward based on the clues he's left behind.  For me, it was the only part of the story when I felt that either of them was in any sort of real peril.<br />
<br />
NGNL certainly isn't the best when it comes to leveraging weakness and vulnerability, but at least it isn't completely blind to the notion of putting limits on the protagonist.  I think NGNL's biggest virtue is that it has a running theme of &quot;brains triumph over (magical) brawn,&quot; which is much more palatable than &quot;I win because my power level is higher than yours.&quot;  (Sora and Shiro are strong, but they're strong in ways that are different than the opponents they face.)</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
